entry.title: Analysis 2/2: Distribution of Original Challenges
entry.content:
Date: Fri Dec 19 00:31:29 2014
Analysis version (challprop-analytics): 7c89a3e
(use git checkout $commit$ if needed)
Back to the experiment page

Distribution of original challenges

The simulation goes this way: there are 10 thousand agents, 100 iterations. Each iteration 20% of agents get a fresh challenge generated by G-O-D, which is 2000 per iteration. These challenges in the beginning are (should be) distributed randomly across all agents in the network. If challenges are not distributed evenly across the network, that may cause buffers of agents lock some challenges and that would explain why we see somewhat low number of secondary propagation of challenges during further simulation. Lets see:

## Checking total number of original challenges:  200000

Looks good in my opinion.

Discussion

The graph with average benefit change does not seem very interesting - the benefit just increases and looks quite different from the one produced by Evo in chalprop-matlab simulation with the same parameters (see presentation, page 9). Also, the average degree and number of knowsLinks in the graph is somewhat suspicious: 2.5 is way too little for what you would expect from 200,000 situations and 100 iterations. There are two possibilities as always - some sort of bug preventing the simulation run correctly or feature of the algorithm.

Anyway, more checking needed. Id say:

  • first of all check the distribution of situation to the agents (is it random);
  • degree distributions and weight distributions
